&gt; I didn’t say only vote in the primaries

Unfortunately the way your arguments frame the conversation, any vote that isn't a vote for the primary candidates is a complete waste.  You were speaking of statistics and third party candidates, but the logic of "vote only for those with the highest chances to win" naturally results in "vote only for the primary candidates" because they have the greatest chance to win.  

&amp;nbsp;

&amp;nbsp;

&gt; and I didn’t say not to fight for your causes 365 days a year against all odds of success: I said when you get into the voting booth, don’t jack off and pretend that you’re changing things.   

These statements conflict.  You need to modify that to "fight for your causes every day of the year, except for when voting is involved." for them to no longer conflict.   

&amp;nbsp;

&amp;nbsp;

&gt; I can practice golf or tennis all year long and bet my money on someone else winning the open this year.  

Not only is this a false equivalency isn't this the anti-thesis of what you are saying?  If you don't believe you have a chance in the first place, why are you wasting all of that effort you could be spending more constructively on something with better odds?  Conversely if you are going to argue that you building yourself up to win one day and that is why you are practicing, this is exactly what I'm saying regarding "throwing your vote away" and you'd be agreeing with me quite directly.

If you're going to say "bet on the scenario with the highest chance to win" then you need to commit to the philosophy.  Otherwise, ironically, you're lessening your own chances.  

&amp;nbsp;

&amp;nbsp;

**There are 3 main general ideologies here to my knowledge.**  

&amp;nbsp;

1.  **Short term:** vote only for what will win right now right now.  Everything not in service of that is a waste.  You're fighting to a subjective "best you can right now" and have full confidence in your actions.
2. **Long term:**  Invest in building momentum and ideas with the idea of winning in the future even if you might lose right now.  You're fighting for the subjective idea of an eventual "greater future" and have full confidence in your actions.   
3.  **Balanced:**  Constantly do a risk vs reward assessment to determine the value of long term vs short term decisions.  Sometimes you'll put up a fight knowing you'll potentially lose for long term value and sometimes you concede and pursue a short term decision that jeopardizes the long term goals in the name of improving the situation before the long term comes to fruition.  Your life is full of nuance and hard choices and rarely are you completely comfortable with results.
